text: For those of you arguing about the 10% theory:  It only took me a couple minutes to find multiple sources explaining how the 10% theory is a myth. There is a multitude of reputable sources you can easily access with a search engine.  You have the internet people, it isn't that hard to look this stuff up for yourself.  That all being said, I will suspend my disbelief when I get a chance to watch this movie in order to try to enjoy it. Using the 10% myth was lazy writing though. They could have used something else to explain how the drug increased her intelligence and gave her super powers.

text: The shame is that movies like this are always disappointing because the enticing premise is just a gimmick. Intelligence isn't just the accumulation of facts/info, but an increased ability to see, reassemble and gain insight/wisdom things from differing, sometimes seemingly contradictory, perspectives. It's not just, "Hey, I can speak French now." Those dopey-ass visuals of people seeing things sped-up or being surrounded by a cyclone of numerals is just sad. I'd like to see a movie that actually consulted real theorists, geniuses and futurists. THAT would be great.

text: This is a splendid idea for a movie. People are saying that it's ripping Limitless, but contrary to it's name, there was very much limits to the drug. The clips from this movie are showing far more depth into the idea of total control over the human brain, and from what I've seen it's more about figuring out how to put a cap on it, rather than exploiting it for some sort of gain. Limitless, was a great movie, but Lucy seems like it will surpass it. I'm hope it does personally, because I looovveee Scarlett Johansson in action movies.

text: While this movie does look interesting (it's like if someone took the movie "limitless" and turned the dial to eleven) my only gripe, and this is a big one, is that it's perpetuating the myth that we only use 10% of our brain. Some neurobiologists even go as far as to call this myth (quote, unquote) "...so wrong it's almost laughable...".  While it is true that at any given moment all of the brain's regions are not firing concurrently, over the course of a day you use 100% of your brain.   What seems to be happening in this film suggests that this "drug" is rewriting her brain to be more efficient overall, and strengthen her current neural pathways as well as others for the future (please correct me if i'm wrong)

text: Not too long ago, we thought the world was flat and flies sprouted from roadkill and feces. First and foremost, "we use only 10% of our brains" is false. This was a claim made 80 years ago in the 1930s and people have been spouting the same outdated information since. If we used only 10% of our brains, we'd be vegetables. We virtually use our entire brain. Different areas are just more active than others at different times for different purposes. As illustrated in functional imaging techniques such as MRIs and PET scans, there's a varying degree of activity among different regions of the brain. In addition to billions of neurons, there are other brain cells(glial cells) continually in use even when we're sleeping. However, past evidence(which is also now proven inaccurate) would suggest that glial cells account for approximately 90% of our brain which could be where the "10%" idea came from because neural cell count was what we used as a measure for determining brain activity; at least when speaking of how much of our brain is in use. That aside, this movie looks awesome.  On a side note, our brain could possibly be the greatest evolutionary asset we have. Evolution has already been proven, there's no arguing that. It makes sense that our brain was able to develop at an exponential rate once we learned how to cook food which provided much more nourishment than raw food. Logically speaking, this could attribute to an exponential increase in cognition. And within the short time frame we achieved this in, there's still soo much we don't know about it. Speaking in context of the movie, our brain is a very power hungry organ that requires 20% of our body's blood supply for nourishment. When whatever substance was released into her bloodstream starts to nourish the brain, maybe it amplified or rewired the synaptic structure of her brain, allowing her to develop total control of her body. She could choose which gene sequences she wants to change her hair, or split her hand in two via mitotic cell division. It looked like there was some kinda cross-species genetics infused in the drug with all that eye flashing stuff going on. Who knows where our technology could take us. All living things are just made up of energy on a subatomic structure anyways. Then again, I'm trying to apply real world logic and facts to a science fiction movie. =)  By the way, Lucy is a name given to the skeletal remains of a female Australopithecus afarensis species of the hominid family dating back to have lived approximately 3.2 million years ago. hrmmm....

text: As a passing observation I would point out that Lucy is a coded name, that can be seen alphanumerically as L=12, U=21, please note that the first two letters are a mirror effect to each other, then C=3 and Y=25. After reducing all letters into numbers, we get 333-7. Of course 3X7=21 and so if we apply this 3 code to 7, we get 21 three times, 21-21-21,  which then reduces to a 3, for each 21, thus producing the second set of 333, that when added + to the first set of 333, then produces a 666.  Lucy, is clear 333 mirror code for 666 in your face.  I cant wait to analyze and observe the story line to this movie.  I just know it is going to be full of interesting findings.

text: I think the "10 percent myth" was founded on the fact that scientists know only as little as much about our brains. And this movie's argument makes sense. Think of your brain as a rubix cube with each piece of square able to rotate in any direction. When you twist the cube around you use 100 percent of it but each piece of square can rotate a lot more faster from a base of 10 rpm per second to 100 rpm per second depending on who's twisting it around. I think the brain is like that, our neural impulses do occur all the time at almost all parts of the brain but that's not all there is to it. If the brain can speed up that transmission of impulses then that's the time where we can truly "utilize 100% of our brain". And I believe it would be terrifyingly astonishing when someone achieves that. The brain's capabilities are unfathomable after all. But if that happens the person would logically die since metabolism will increase greatly too

text: Hasta ayer pude darme la oportunidad de ver Lucy, el exitoso filme de Luc Besson,ME FASCINO!!! no cabe duda que el genial director Francés no pierde su sentido del humor, la película de un ritmo vertiginoso es una mezcla perfecta de ciencia ficción, acción, aventura, peligros y conceptos metafísicos a morir!!! Desde el titulo que refiere al mas antiguo resto de esqueleto humano que se ha podido encontrar en nuestro planeta hasta ahora, con aproximadamente 3.2 millones de años de edad, parte una historia basada en el famoso mito de que nuestro cerebro solo ocupa el 10% de nuestro cerebro (mito por que el cerebro humano es utilizado al 100%, mas no funciona al 100% de toda su capacidad todo el tiempo, ni mucho menos refiere toda la información acumulada y función total de las células al 100% todo el tiempo en todos los individuos de este planeta). Pero nuestra "Lucy" moderna (la preciosísima y talentosísima de Scarlett Johansson) si logra realizarlo, el filme es tambien un muy pequeño homenaje bien hecho a "2001 Odisea del Espacio" de Stanley Kubrick, no como la cochinada mal hecha de :Gravity", "Lucy" no intenta ser ni pretenciosa, ni filosófica, ni trascendental, ni retrospectiva, ni analítica, como todo el cine de Andrei Tarkovski o Krzysztof Kieślowski, Luc Besson lo único que quiere es entretenernos y que reflexionemos un poco sobre esos bellísimos conceptos metafísicos que nos hacen sentir vivos, universales, formando parte de un ente que lo ve y lo siente todo.

text: Lots of people have already said this on this forum but I feel the need to back them up as a scientist myself. Humans use 100% of our brains. Every human does.  Why would evolution favor a human body that produces (and therefore wastes extreme amounts of energy both in production and maintenance) of an organ 10 times bigger than is used? Simply put, it wouldn't.  To simplify this concept it's like saying the human species has developed with 10 individual brains in our heads but we only use 1 of those. The other 9 are just completely useless to 99.999% of the population but for some weird fluke reason evolution has ignored this massive waste of energy and continues to produce humans with a brain 10 times larger than is used. For a more precise analysis of the ridiculousness of this claim log onto any scientific database and read any research papers produced in the last 20 years on the topic.

text: The criticism on the whole "10% of your brain being false" is not really the problem of the film, imo. The "10% Usage of the brain" idea was used as a "profound" theme of sort rather than boasting it as fact. I say that because people say it's wrong like no one knew that. And of course, I know there are people who believe it to be true. However, entertainment has universally (no medium is safe) resorted to artist license to make their content seem more interesting. It's not the fault of entertainment, though. It's mostly our fault when we read and watch entertainment, and we actually believe some of the subjects they talk about.   However, the movie just isn't good. The film spews philosophical garbage that seemed more pretentious and faulty rather than enlightening and thought provoking. Maybe if they had reconsidered some parts of the film, it would be a bit more fascinating. However, I don't know for sure.

text: Perhaps I'm using 10 percent of 10 percent of what's left of my 10 percent brain (to fantasize about Scarjo. Naturally. I am human, y'know.) But my ten percent of whatever brain is left can see right through the premise of this movie. A woman like Scarjo can't be called super intelligent and just blow away some foreign guy just cos he's foreign and male and therefore more human than Scarjo. An intelligent, ahem, PERSON does NOT use violence as a last resort. Isaac Asimov himself once wrote in the novel Foundation "Violence is the last resort for the incompetent." This is a MAN who came up with this saying ALL BY HIMSELF. And he used his ten percent WISELY. So can it be called chauvinist to say that because of the Lucy film, the only thing women understand with their ten percent...is violence? Is this the core message of the film or did I get something Lost in Translation? (Ouch.)
